article.description: Lisa Leslie scored 22 points with 11 rebounds and a career-high nine assists, just missing the fifth triple-double in WNBA history, to lead the Sparks to an 86-63 rout of the Mercury.
article.headline: Phoenix loses fifth straight game
article.linkText: Leslie nears triple-double in Sparks' rout of Mercury
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An offensive adjustment by the Los Angeles Sparks almost enabled Lisa Leslie to achieve a triple-double.

Leslie had 22 points, 11 rebounds and a career-high nine assists to lead the Sparks to an 86-63 rout of the Phoenix Mercury on Saturday night.

"We've really been working on and improving on getting the ball to me this week," Leslie said. "I try to tell [my teammates], 'If you look for me, I can drive and help you guys.' It really worked."

Leslie, who has been bothered all season by a groin injury, needed one assist for her second triple-double and the fifth in WNBA history.

"It's the first time I really thought she looked comfortable," Sparks guard Tamecka Dixon said.

Chamique Holdsclaw, the WNBA's leading scorer, added 19 points. Tamika Whitmore had 16 points as the Sparks (9-6) shot 55.4 percent for their sixth victory in eight games.

Kamila Vodichkova scored 16 points for the Mercury (3-11), which has lost five consecutive games and six of seven. Penny Taylor added 14 points and Anna DeForge had 11.

Diana Taurasi, the WNBA's second-leading scorer, missed 11-of-12 shots and finished with five points. Taurasi did not score until 3:56 remained in the first half.

The Sparks used an 11-2 surge to move ahead 19-11 with 11:46 left in the first half. Leslie scored five points during the run while Phoenix made only two free throws.

The Mercury narrowed its deficit to 23-22 but a 10-2 spurt extended the Sparks' lead to 33-24 with 4:47 remaining in the first half.

Los Angeles began the second half with a 14-1 run to build a 60-37 lead with 14:44 to play.

Phoenix's Maria Stepanova played in her first WNBA game since 2001 and scored nine points. Stepanova left the team during training camp in 2002 when she became pregnant and played in Russia and the Czech Republic.
